    pearls: ["The Surviving Sepsis Campaign hour-1 bundle requires: measure lactate, obtain blood cultures, administer broad-spectrum antibiotics, begin 30 mL/kg crystalloid for hypotension or lactate >=4, and start vasopressors if hypotensive during or after fluid resuscitation","Septic shock is defined as sepsis with persistent hypotension requiring vasopressors to maintain MAP >=65 AND lactate >2 mmol/L despite adequate volume resuscitation -- mortality exceeds 40%","Procalcitonin helps differentiate bacterial (elevated) from viral (normal) infections and can guide antibiotic duration -- a declining PCT supports antibiotic discontinuation","qSOFA (quick SOFA) is a bedside screening tool: altered mentation + SBP <=100 + RR >=22; 2 or more criteria should prompt further evaluation for organ dysfunction","Lactate clearance of >10% over 2-4 hours is associated with improved outcomes and indicates adequate resuscitation; rising lactate requires escalation of care","Do NOT delay antibiotics to obtain cultures if cultures cannot be drawn within 45 minutes -- antibiotic administration within the first hour is the single most impactful intervention"],
    quiz: [
      {
        question: "A patient in the ED meets qSOFA criteria with altered mentation and SBP 88 mmHg. Initial lactate is 4.8 mmol/L. Which intervention takes highest priority?",
        options: ["Obtain CT scan to identify infection source","Administer broad-spectrum IV antibiotics within 1 hour and begin 30 mL/kg crystalloid resuscitation","Start a vasopressor infusion immediately","Consult infectious disease for antibiotic selection"],
        correct: 1,
        rationale: "The Surviving Sepsis Campaign hour-1 bundle prioritizes blood cultures followed by immediate broad-spectrum antibiotics and 30 mL/kg crystalloid for patients with hypotension or lactate >=4 mmol/L. Vasopressors are indicated if hypotension persists after fluid resuscitation, not before. Antibiotic administration within 1 hour is the most impactful single intervention."
      },
      {
        question: "A septic patient on norepinephrine has a lactate of 6.2 mmol/L that increases to 7.8 mmol/L two hours later despite IV fluid resuscitation. What does the rising lactate indicate?",
        options: ["The patient is recovering and clearing lactate normally","Tissue hypoperfusion is worsening and resuscitation is inadequate","The lactate elevation is a normal lab variation","Antibiotics are working and bacterial lysis is releasing lactate"],
        correct: 1,
        rationale: "Rising lactate indicates worsening tissue hypoperfusion and ongoing anaerobic metabolism. Lactate clearance of >10% over 2-4 hours is the therapeutic target. A rising lactate requires escalation of care -- increased vasopressor dosing, additional fluid boluses, reassessment of source control, and consideration of adjunctive therapies."
      },
      {
        question: "Which mechanism best explains the capillary leak and distributive shock seen in sepsis?",
        options: ["Direct bacterial invasion of blood vessel walls causing structural damage","Cytokine-mediated endothelial activation causing glycocalyx degradation, adhesion molecule upregulation, and loss of barrier function","Allergic reaction to bacterial antigens causing mast cell degranulation","Autoimmune antibodies targeting the vascular endothelium"],
        correct: 1,
        rationale: "Sepsis-induced capillary leak results from pro-inflammatory cytokines (TNF-alpha, IL-1, IL-6) activating endothelial cells, degrading the glycocalyx, upregulating adhesion molecules, and disrupting tight junctions. This increases vascular permeability, allowing plasma to extravasate into the interstitium, causing the intravascular volume depletion and distributive shock characteristic of sepsis."
      },
    ]
